<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-120-165 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 571 994</DOCID><JOURNAL>Proceedings of the IEEE  July 1991 v79 n7 p1009(10).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Uses of precise time and frequency in power systems. (part of aspecial issue on time and frequency) (Technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wilson, Robert E.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The accurate measurement of time and frequency is important in theoperation of electric power systems.andP;  The reliable transfer ofelectrical power from the generation point to the consumerrequires the measurement of power system frequency in manylocations.andP;  The high voltages require elaborate protection andcontrol systems to guard against short and open circuits.andP;  Precisetimekeeping networks help analyze power system operations bysynchronizing clocks on recording instruments.andP;  All generators andlarge motors must be close to speed synchronism and voltage levelsmust remain near nominal values.andP;  A power system's stable responseto small and large perturbations is critical.andP;  State vectormeasurements require clock synchronizations of 5 to 46microseconds.andP;  Research on one microsecond timekeeping continues.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TimingTime MeasurementFrequencyPower SystemsPower Plants.andO;Feature:   illustrationcharttable.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>